MEDMATCH — Healthcare Staffing Intelligence Agent
Project Brief
Build a multi-agent system that automates the core workflow of a healthcare staffing platform: given a facility's open shift requirements, the agent autonomously searches for matching clinicians, verifies their credentials, ranks candidates, and produces a structured placement recommendation — with a clean web UI to demo it.
This project is designed as a portfolio piece for an Agentic AI Engineer application at Medfinder.

Directives for Claude Code

1. Project Overview
Project Name: MedMatch Agent
Stack: Python backend, FastAPI, LangChain/LangGraph, Claude API (claude-sonnet-4-20250514), React frontend
Deployment: Host on HuggingFace Spaces (Gradio) OR Vercel (frontend) + Railway/Render (backend)
Repo: Public GitHub repo with clean README
What it does in plain English:
A recruiter pastes in a shift requirement (e.g. "ICU RN, night shift, ACLS certified, Boston MA, this weekend"). The agent breaks this into subtasks, runs them in parallel using specialised sub-agents, and returns a ranked shortlist of matching candidates with reasoning — all transparently shown in the UI so the recruiter can see exactly how the agent thinks.

2. Agent Architecture
Build a supervisor + worker multi-agent pattern using LangGraph:
SupervisorAgent
├── RequirementParserAgent    — extracts structured fields from free-text shift request
├── CandidateMatcherAgent     — scores synthetic candidates against requirements
├── CredentialVerifierAgent   — checks license validity, certifications, expiry dates
├── AvailabilityAgent         — checks candidate availability against shift window
└── RankingAgent              — produces final ranked list with reasoning per candidate
Each agent is a discrete node in a LangGraph StateGraph. The supervisor routes between them based on output state.

3. Module Specifications
Module 1 — requirement_parser.py

Input: raw free-text string from recruiter
Uses Claude to extract: specialty, role, certifications_required[], location, shift_type, shift_date, urgency
Output: structured ShiftRequirement Pydantic model
Edge case handling: ambiguous location, missing dates, multiple specialties

Module 2 — candidate_store.py

Synthetic dataset of 50 clinicians (generate on first run using Claude)
Each candidate has: name, specialty, certifications[], license_state, license_expiry, years_experience, availability[], last_placement, rating
Store as JSON, load into memory at startup
No real PHI — all synthetic

Module 3 — matcher_agent.py

Takes ShiftRequirement + full candidate list
Scores each candidate on: specialty match, certification match, location/license match, availability
Returns top 10 candidates with raw scores

Module 4 — credential_verifier_agent.py

Takes candidate list from matcher
Simulates credential verification: checks license expiry vs shift date, flags missing required certs
Returns verification status per candidate: VERIFIED, EXPIRING_SOON, MISSING_CERT
Add a mock "NPI lookup" tool call to make it feel real

Module 5 — availability_agent.py

Checks candidate availability[] against shift window
Flags conflicts, confirms matches
Returns availability status per candidate

Module 6 — ranking_agent.py

Takes verified + available candidates
Uses Claude to produce a final ranked list with a one-sentence reasoning per candidate
Output: RankedShortlist with top 5 candidates, scores, reasoning, and flags

Module 7 — supervisor.py (LangGraph orchestration)

Defines AgentState TypedDict
Builds StateGraph connecting all agents
Supervisor decides next node based on current state
Tracks execution steps for transparency display in UI

Module 8 — api.py (FastAPI)

POST /match — accepts shift requirement text, runs full agent pipeline, returns ranked shortlist + execution trace
GET /candidates — returns full synthetic candidate pool
GET /health — ping endpoint
WebSocket endpoint for streaming agent step updates to frontend

Module 9 — React Frontend

Clean, minimal UI — not a demo toy, looks like a real internal tool
Left panel: text input for shift requirement + submit button
Centre: live agent execution trace (streaming, step by step as each agent runs)
Right panel: final ranked shortlist cards with candidate name, match score, verification status, reasoning
Each card expandable to show full candidate profile
Color coding: green (verified, available), yellow (expiring soon), red (conflict)
Mobile responsive


